            reviewDate: 'May 21, 2024',
            semester: 'spring 2024',
            review: "This was my last serious course in OMSCS, one more easy course and I'm done for the entire program.\nSome background: I have taken some challenging courses in through my time in this program (RL, GA, GIOS), I wouldn't call these super challenging, but did create some hiccups as I came from non-CS undergrad background (even though I code in my fulltime job).\nThis has been the most challenging class for me, but I do like it a lot.\nWhat I liked about it:\n\nYou really learn stuffs, useful stuffs, and will have a much better understanding of parallel programing and distributed system in general.\nThe project are rewarding and cements what you learned from lectures and textbook. You will realize that if you understand more, the better performance your code will be.\nEven though there are private test cases for projects, but it's not too \"edge-gy\", meaning that you don't need to spend hours to figure out edge cases that are trivial. It is generally easy to get most of points from compiling and public/private tests, the meaty part is the performance part.\nTextbook of this course and some reading materials are enjoyable to read (will be better if without any time limitation)\nThe TA team are super clear, project instructions are very clear as well.\nCurve is generous, if you do your work, you get what you deserve.\n\nWhat I didn't like:\n\nLast project was graded on comparative performance, will be a time sink if you try to outperform your peers.\nExams, are pretty challenging and are pretty challenging to get a grasp on, 50/100 was like a average, but they are open book, open internet, so you don't have to memorize.\nThe last part of the course wasn't very well structured, it feels like crunching a bunch of things in a short period of time. I get it... it makes the learning curve not as steep for the first half of the course, but I did not enjoy the pace of last 3 weeks.\n\nSome facts:\n\nUnless you are a rock star, prepare many weekends doing nothing but projects. I had a regular fulltime job which is a little time demanding and I had to spend some weekends immersing in the projects.\nThe learning curve is very steep in the first half of the course, there are so much you need to learn before you can even do your projects: OpenMP, CUDA, MPI. Also, it is challenging to think in parallel programming's fashion, not to mention the algos with different types of analysis comparing to serial programs.\n",
